{
  "text": "Membrane proteins are encoded by over 25% of all sequenced open reading frames and constitute the majority of known drug targets [CITATION_1] . Therefore, tools providing a greater understanding of membrane proteins may benefit cell biology research and pharmacological development [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The advance of methods for labeling proteins by genetic fusion is expanding the understanding of protein function in complex intracellular environments (see recent reviews) [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Current reporter proteins such as carrier proteins (i.e. peptidyl PCP or acyl ACP), tetra-cysteine tags (i.e. Fluorescein and Resorufin Arsenical Helical binders), O 6 -alkylguanine-DNA alkyltransferase (AGT), photoactivatable proteins and others (reviewed by Chapman et al) allow more flexibility than originally available with GFP [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . However, visualization of multiple pools of the same protein through space and time can still be technically challenging and new options could only benefit this expanding field.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "32834694",
